Grading scheme:
[
  {
    "title": "Proving finite termination",
    "points": 2,
    "desc": "For giving a well-founded monovariant and applying it rigorously. A standard full-credit argument lets $r$ be the number of entries greater than $1$ and $P$ the product of all entries: if $d=\\gcd(m,n)=1$, then $P$ is unchanged and $r$ decreases; if $d>1$, then $P$ decreases and $r$ cannot increase. Thus $(r,P)$ decreases lexicographically. Award $1$ of the $2$ points for identifying the two monotone quantities but not fully ruling out an infinite sequence, or for an equivalent monovariant with a minor justification gap."
  },
  {
    "title": "Showing exactly one non-unit remains",
    "points": 1,
    "desc": "For proving both sides of the terminal-state claim: at termination there are at most one entry greater than $1$, while there cannot be zero because every legal move leaves at least one of its two outputs greater than $1$."
  },
  {
    "title": "Identifying a prime-valuation invariant",
    "points": 1,
    "desc": "For fixing a prime $p$ and proposing the invariant $I_p=\\gcd(\\nu_p(t_1),\\ldots,\\nu_p(t_{2026}))$, or an equivalent invariant that determines the exponent of $p$ in the final number."
  },
  {
    "title": "Proving the valuation invariant",
    "points": 2,
    "desc": "For showing that if the selected entries have $p$-adic valuations $x\\le y$, then the new valuations are $x$ and $y-x$, and using $\\gcd(x,y-x)=\\gcd(x,y)$ to prove that $I_p$ is unchanged. Award $1$ of the $2$ points for the correct valuation update with the global invariance conclusion incomplete."
  },
  {
    "title": "Determining the final value of $M$",
    "points": 1,
    "desc": "For deducing $\\nu_p(M)=\\gcd_i\\nu_p(a_i)$ for every prime $p$ and concluding that these exponents uniquely determine $M$, hence make it independent of all choices."
  }
]

