Problem:
Determine all functions $f:\mathbb{R}_{>0}\to\mathbb{R}_{>0}$ such that, for every $x,y>0$,
\[
  \sqrt{\frac{x^2+f(y)^2}{2}}
  \ge \frac{f(x)+y}{2}
  \ge \sqrt{x f(y)}.
\]

Grading scheme:
[
  {
    "title": "Finding and checking the solution family",
    "points": 1,
    "desc": "For identifying the complete family $f(x)=x+c$ with $c\\ge0$ and verifying it by the quadratic-mean--arithmetic-mean--geometric-mean inequality applied to $x$ and $y+c$. The identity function $c=0$ must be included."
  },
  {
    "title": "Forcing the second-iterate relation",
    "points": 1,
    "desc": "For substituting $(x,y)=(f(t),t)$, observing that the two outer expressions coincide, and deriving $f(f(t))=2f(t)-t$."
  },
  {
    "title": "Deriving arithmetic-progression iterates",
    "points": 1,
    "desc": "For defining $d(t)=f(t)-t$, proving $f^m(t)=t+m d(t)$ for all $m\\ge0$, and using positivity of all iterates to conclude $d(t)\\ge0$."
  },
  {
    "title": "Showing all positive increments are equal",
    "points": 2,
    "desc": "For proving that if $d(x)=A>0$ and $d(y)=B>0$, then $A=B$. In the reference route, applying the right inequality to iterates yields $(\\sqrt{x+mA}-\\sqrt{y+(n+1)B})^2\\ge B-A$; a bracketing argument with the vanishing gaps of the square-root sequence rules out $A<B$, and symmetry finishes. Award $1$ of the $2$ points for deriving a correct decisive inequality or equivalent comparison with a substantial but incomplete equality argument."
  },
  {
    "title": "Separating fixed and shifted points",
    "points": 1,
    "desc": "For reducing to $f(t)\\in\\{t,t+D\\}$ for a fixed $D>0$ and proving that a shifted point $x$ and a fixed point $y$ must satisfy $|x-y|>D$, using the appropriate one of the two original inequalities."
  },
  {
    "title": "Eliminating mixed behavior",
    "points": 1,
    "desc": "For using the separation result to show that every point within distance $D$ of a shifted point is also shifted, propagating through overlapping intervals to all of $\\mathbb{R}_{>0}$, and concluding that the function is either the identity or $f(x)=x+D$ everywhere."
  }
]

[
  {
    "title": "Reducing to radical-minimal terms",
    "points": 1,
    "desc": "For introducing a redundancy relation such as $a_m\\prec a_n$ when $m<n$ and $\\operatorname{rad}(a_m)\\mid\\operatorname{rad}(a_n)$, and proving that an integer $x\\ge a_1$ occurs in the sequence exactly when it shares a nontrivial divisor with every $\\prec$-minimal earlier term below $x$."
  },
  {
    "title": "Proving that large primes do not occur in minimal terms",
    "points": 3,
    "desc": "For proving the key lemma that a $\\prec$-minimal term cannot be divisible by a prime $p>a_1^2$. The $3$ points may be awarded as follows: (i) construct $b\\in[a_1,a_n)$ from $a_n=pc$ and a prime $q\\mid\\gcd(a_1,a_n)$ (for example, take $b=c$ if $c\\ge a_1$, and otherwise the least $q^k c\\ge a_1$) and justify $b<a_n$; (ii) use induction to show that $p$ divides no minimal predecessor, hence $b$ satisfies all nonredundant gcd conditions and therefore occurs in the sequence; (iii) prove $\\operatorname{rad}(b)\\mid\\operatorname{rad}(a_n)$ and $b<a_n$, contradicting minimality. A correct equivalent finite-prime lemma receives the same credit."
  },
  {
    "title": "Classifying terms by small-prime signatures",
    "points": 2,
    "desc": "For letting $\\mathcal P$ be the finite set of primes at most $a_1^2$, defining $S(a)=\\{p\\in\\mathcal P:p\\mid a\\}$ and $\\mathcal F=\\{S(a_n):n\\ge1\\}$, and proving the exact characterization $a$ occurs if and only if $a\\ge a_1$ and $S(a)\\in\\mathcal F$. Award $1$ of the $2$ points for showing that only finitely many primes matter or that membership depends on $S(a)$, but not proving the converse characterization."
  },
  {
    "title": "Deducing periodicity and the translation law",
    "points": 1,
    "desc": "For taking $L=\\prod_{p\\in\\mathcal P}p$, observing that sequence membership is periodic modulo $L$, letting $T$ be the number of occurring residue classes, and proving that the $T$-th next term after $a_n$ is exactly $a_n+L$, so $a_{n+T}=a_n+L$ for every $n$."
  }
]
